28","1516":"1516","1549":"1549","1527":"1527","1603":"1603","Slade, Glamorgan, Wales":"Slade, Glamorgan, Wales","Berrynarbor, Devon, England":"Berrynarbor, Devon, England"},"en":{"1516–":"1516–Deceased","1514–1579":"1514–1579","1516–Female":"1516–Deceased","1518–Male":"1518–Deceased","1525–Female":"1525–Deceased","1527–1590":"1527–1590","1528–Female":"1528–Deceased","1512–Male":"1512–Deceased","1544–1603":"1544–1603","1487–1565":"1487–1565","1490–1530":"1490–1530","1590":"1590","1490":"1490","1558":"1558","1525":"1525","1514":"1514","1579":"1579","1512":"1512","1544":"1544","1620":"1620","1587":"1587","1565":"1565","1487":"1487","about 1545":"about 1545","1585":"1585","1530":"1530","1518":"1518","1528":"1528","1516":"1516","1549":"1549","1527":"1527","1603":"1603","Slade, Glamorgan, Wales":"Slade, Glamorgan, Wales","Berrynarbor, Devon, England":"Berrynarbor, Devon, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Berry","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Béara</b> ‘descendant of <i>Béara</i>’, a personal name of unexplained etymology; or, in some cases, perhaps an Anglicized form of Irish and Manx <b>Ó Beargha</b>. Compare   Barry   1.","Scottish and northern Irish: variant of   Barrie  .","English: habitational name from any of several places called in Devon named with Old English <i>byrig</i>, dative case of <i>burh</i> ‘fortified manor house, stronghold’, such as Berry Pomeroy and Berrynarbor."],"variants":[{"name":"Berrey","meanings":["English: variant of   Berry  ."]},{"name":"Barry","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Donal, Aidan, Ciaran, Eoin, John Patrick, Kaitlin, Kieran, Murphy, Aileen, Brigid, Caitlin.","Irish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Beargha</b> ‘descendant of <i>Beargh</i>’, a byname meaning ‘plunderer’.","Irish and Manx: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Báire</b> ‘descendant of <i>Báire</i>’, a short form of either of two Gaelic personal names, <i>Bairrfhionn</i> or <i>Fionnbharr</i>, both meaning ‘fair-topped’. This may also be the source of the Manx name <i>Barry</i>, whose family's main seat was Ballavarry in Kirk Andreas."]},{"name":"Bery","meanings":["English: variant of   Berry  .","Hungarian (<b>Béry</b>): habitational name for someone from any of various places called Bér, in Baranya, Komárom, Nógrád, Pest, Vas, or Zala counties."]},{"name":"Beery","meanings":["Irish: Anglicized form of <b>Ó Béara</b>. See   Berry   and   O'Berry  .","Americanized form of Swiss German   Bieri  ."]},{"name":"Berrie","meanings":["Scottish:","(Glasgow): from Middle English or Older Scots <i>(atte) beri</i> ‘(at the) manor house’, see   Berry  .","variant   Barrie  ."]}]},{"name":"Anne","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["variant of   Anne  , in common use as a given name in most European languages. Among people with a classical education, it has from time to time been associated with  Virgil's  Aeneid, where it is borne by the sister of  Dido , Queen of Carthage. This Phoenician name may ultimately be of Semitic origin, and thus related to the biblical <i>Anne</i>. However, the connection, if it exists, is indirect rather than direct."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":33,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":42,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705207,"age":69,"year":"1585","julianDay":2299970,"title":"The First English Colony is Established in America","description":"England established its first colony in North America in 1585 as a way to generate additional wealth. The colony was named Virginia, after the virgin Queen Elizabeth I.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705208,"age":71,"year":"1587","julianDay":2300700,"title":"Elizabeth I Signs Death Warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots","description":"Elizabeth I signed the death warrant for Mary, Queen of Scots, on February 1, 1587, as she was found guilty of plotting to assasinate Elizabeth. Mary, Queen of Scots, was beheaded at Fotheringhay Castle in England on February 8, 1587.","url":"https://www.elizabethi.org/mary_queen_of_scots/","urlTitle":"Elizabeth I.org - Mary Queen of Scots","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705212,"age":104,"year":"1620","julianDay":2312753,"title":"The Pilgrims Board the Mayflower","description":"\"The Pilgrims boarded the Mayflower in search of religious freedom in the New World in September 1620. The Mayflower set sail from Plymouth, England, with 102 passengers, 40 of whom called themselves \"\"Saints.\"\" After two stormy months at sea, the ship reached the New World. Nearly half of the group died during their first winter due to malnutrition and the harsh New England winter.\"","url":"https://www.themayflowersociety.org/the-pilgrims/pilgrim-history","urlTitle":"The Mayflower Society - Pilgrim History","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne Berry was born in 1516, in Berrynarbor, Devon, England, her father, Nicholas Berry, was 30 and her mother, Elizabeth Bowden, was 27. She married Griffith Bowen about 1545. The